      "writtenOn": "2020-03-04T04:05:04Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I noticed this issue while debugging with s.stopped and s.errC, and was going to send a separate CL with the idea. I\u0027d like to remove s.ErrC(), but Start() returns a channel where the user can read to find if the server has been terminated. Let\u0027s continue this topic in a separate CL.\n\n```\nfunc (s *Server) Start(ctx) \u003c- chan error {\n  // this is the channel that the user can use to get notified\n  // for the termination of the server.\n  ret :\u003d make(chan error, 1)\n\n  ....\n  go serveLoop(ctx)\n  go func() {\n    for {\n      select {\n      case \u003c-ctx.Done():\n        # Perhaps, this should repeat invoking s.Close(), with exponential backoff,\n        # until Close() returns nil?\n        s.Close()\n      case sErr :\u003d \u003c- s.errC:\n        // notify the user that the server has been terminated  \n        if ctx.Err() !\u003d nil {\n          ret \u003c- context.Canceled\n        } else {\n          ret \u003c- sErr\n        }\n      }\n  }()\n  return ret\n}\n```",
